# Spec-Driven Development (SDD)

This project uses **Spec-Driven Development** via
[GitHub spec-kit](https://github.com/github/spec-kit). SDD makes the
*specification* the durable source of truth: you write down what you're
building and why, turn that into a technical plan, break the plan into
tasks, and only then implement. The spec outlives any single coding
session and keeps both humans and agents from drifting.

## Where SDD sits relative to DDD and TDD

These three are layers of the same pipeline, not competitors:

```
SDD   →  WHAT & WHY    spec → plan → tasks         (this file + spec-kit)
DDD   →  HOW (model)   aggregates, value objects,  (general/ddd.md)
                       layering, ubiquitous language
TDD   →  HOW (build)   red → green → refactor,     (general/tdd.md)
                       one task at a time
```

- **SDD** is the front of the funnel. It produces a precise spec, a plan,
  and an ordered task list.
- **DDD** is how you *design* each task's solution — the domain model,
  the layering, the value objects.
- **TDD** is how you *implement* each task — a failing test first, then
  the code.

So the full loop for a feature is:
`/speckit.specify` → `/speckit.plan` → `/speckit.tasks` → for each task:
**model with DDD → build with TDD**.

## The spec-kit workflow

Once installed (see "Setup" below), your agent gains these slash commands:

| Command | Purpose |
| --- | --- |
| `/speckit.constitution` | Establish the project's non-negotiable principles. |
| `/speckit.specify` | Describe *what* to build and *why* (not how). Creates `specs/NNN-feature/spec.md`. |
| `/speckit.clarify` | Resolve ambiguities in the spec before planning. |
| `/speckit.plan` | Establish the technical approach. Creates `plan.md`, `data-model.md`, `contracts/`, etc. |
| `/speckit.tasks` | Break the plan into an ordered, reviewable task list (`tasks.md`). |
| `/speckit.analyze` | Cross-check spec ↔ plan ↔ tasks for gaps and contradictions. |
| `/speckit.implement` | Execute the tasks. **This is where DDD + TDD apply.** |

Artifacts land under `specs/NNN-feature-name/`.

## The constitution — point it at this instruction tree

spec-kit's `/speckit.constitution` writes
`.specify/memory/constitution.md`: the immutable principles every spec and
implementation must honour. **Do not duplicate our rules there.** This
project already has its governing principles in the instruction tree —
make the constitution *reference* them:

- Architecture & layering → `general/architecture.md`
- Domain modelling → `general/ddd.md`
- Test-driven micro-implementation → `general/tdd.md`
- Coding conventions → `general/coding-conventions.md`
- Language specifics → `<language>/` (e.g. `python/`)

A good constitution for this project is short: "Follow the principles in
`{{ ai_folder }}/instructions/`. Specs must be implementable within the
DDD layering. Every task is built test-first." Then add anything truly
project-specific.

## Setup

Install spec-kit's slash commands into this project (one time):

```sh
just sdd-init
```

That runs spec-kit's initializer for your agent. After it finishes, the
slash commands above are available, and a `.specify/` directory appears
with templates and the constitution. Commit `.specify/` and `specs/`.

> spec-kit is an external, actively-maintained tool. We deliberately do
> **not** vendor its templates here — `just sdd-init` always pulls the
> current version. Re-run it to upgrade.

## When to use SDD vs. just doing the work

- **Use the full SDD loop** for net-new features, anything with real
  ambiguity, or work that several people / sessions will touch.
- **Skip straight to DDD + TDD** for small, well-understood changes and
  bug fixes — writing a one-line spec for a typo fix is ceremony. Use
  judgement; SDD is a tool, not a tax.
